quotes.!modcollection:
Hello there!

Someone thinks it's important for you to understand why subscribing to mod collections is a terrible idea.

Read more about it here: https://discord.com/channels/214523379766525963/632790371256238120/979205473205092352

tl;dr: Mod collections are often outdated and poorly curated by users who may not realize their games have issues until something breaks catastrophically.
quotes.!binary:
```ansi
How to binary search
[0;32m1)[0;90m Test on a new save to see if the issue is easily reproducible. Proceed if it is.
[0;32m2)[0;90m Remove half of your active mods, ensuring dependencies are still fulfilled.
[0;32m3)[0;90m Test on a new save (loading an existing save will likely result in numerous unrelated errors).
[0;32m4a)[0;90m If [0;31merror is [4;90mstill[0;90m present[0;90m, [0;34mrepeat from step [4;90m2[0;90m.
[0;32m4b)[0;90m If [0;31merror is [4;90mno longer[0;90m present, [0;34mswap to the half you removed in step [4;90m2[0;90m, then repeat from step [4;90m3[0;90m.
[0;32m5)[0;90m Repeat until you identify the mod(s) causing the issue.

Note: It may not be possible to identify the exact mod or combination of mods that are causing the error, but it should be possible to significantly narrow down the possibilities, allowing for more targeted testing.
```

quotes.!cleanslate:
When developing new mods, please make sure you're using the minimum possible mod list, preferably only direct dependencies for your mod. This not only cuts down on load times but minimizes the chances that edge case incompatibilities make it difficult to understand whether you did something wrong or your mod is being broken by an outside mod. Definitely do not use performance mods like Performance Analyzer until you are feature-complete and profiling for performance.

Also, it's a good idea to ensure that you have a clean error log at all times. Whether you ignore errors or not as a player is your prerogative, but ignoring errors while developing mods is a fast ticket to sanity loss. Make sure you have no errors before you start developing, address errors immediately when they pop up, and work your error list from top to bottom as later errors tend to be collateral damage from an earlier failure.
quotes.!workspace: Consider loading the entire `Rimworld` folder into a workspace so you can search through all Defs at once, both vanilla and locally modded. Notepad++, VS Code, or any other modern IDE can do this. Example shown is in VS Code. https://cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/326892498096095233/1105722523519295569/Animation20.gif
quotes.!chatgpt: Programs such as ChatGPT are language processors and not true AI; they will confidently spew nonsense that only a true expert can tell from fiction, thus they are strongly discouraged when you are trying to learn a new technical skill such as coding or mod-making as they can make it harder to learn how to do things correctly.
quotes.!sequence: Try to avoid using `PatchOperationSequence` because it can obfuscate errors and make it difficult to figure out what's wrong. You only need it if you are sequencing multiple patches off of a PatchOperationFindMod or PatchOperationConditional, and in the former case if you have enough patches you should consider using LoadFolders.xml instead. Please see https://rimworldwiki.com/wiki/Modding_Tutorials/PatchOperations for more information.
